[49m[38;5;9m- 534     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter13.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter13.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 8: Dead letter queue and failure handling.** When any step in the extraction pipeline fails after Step Functions' built-in retries (typically 3 attempts with exponential backoff), the execution must not silently disappear. A failed execution sends the article ID, the failed step name, and the error details to an SQS dead letter queue. A CloudWatch alarm fires when DLQ depth exceeds a threshold (e.g., 10 messages in 5 minutes), paging the on-call engineer. A separate reprocessor Lambda can be triggered manually or on a schedule to replay failed articles once the underlying issue is resolved. Without this, articles that fail due to transient issues (Comprehend Medical throttling, Neptune connection timeouts) are permanently lost from the graph.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Step Functions state machine definition includes a Catch block on each step:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // On failure after retries, transition to the SendToDLQ state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m STATE send_to_dlq:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     INPUT = {article_id, failed_step, error_message, execution_arn, attempt_count}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     send to SQS DLQ: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         article_id:     INPUT.article_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         failed_step:    INPUT.failed_step,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         error_message:  INPUT.error_message,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         execution_arn:  INPUT.execution_arn,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         timestamp:      current timestamp,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         s3_document_key: lookup S3 key for article_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // CloudWatch Alarm: ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible > 10 for 5 minutes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Action: SNS notification to on-call team
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Reprocessor Lambda (triggered manually or on schedule):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION reprocess_dlq_messages():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     WHILE messages available in DLQ:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         message = receive from DLQ (max 10 per batch)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Restart the pipeline from the beginning for this article.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The document is already in S3, so no re-fetch needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         start Step Functions execution with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             input = {document_s3_key: message.s3_document_key, is_replay: TRUE}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         delete message from DLQ
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 9: Retraction monitoring.** Published papers get retracted. When a paper that contributed to your knowledge graph is retracted, the relationships it supports may be invalid. A scheduled Lambda (daily is sufficient) queries PubMed for newly retracted articles using the "Retracted Publication" publication type filter. When a retraction is detected: the Lambda queries Neptune for all edges citing the retracted PMID. If the retracted paper was the sole source for an edge (support_count = 1), that edge's status changes to "RETRACTED". If other papers also support the edge, the evidence_score is recalculated excluding the retracted source and the retracted provenance entry is flagged. This is a patient safety concern: retracted findings (e.g., the Wakefield MMR-autism paper) can persist in knowledge graphs and influence clinical queries if not actively monitored.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION check_retractions():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Query PubMed for recently retracted publications (last 7 days)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retracted_pmids = call PubMed E-utilities esearch with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         database = "pubmed"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         query    = "Retracted Publication[pt] AND last 7 days[CRDT]"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         retmax   = 500
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each pmid in retracted_pmids:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Find all edges in Neptune that cite this PMID as provenance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         affected_edges = query Neptune:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MATCH edges WHERE provenance contains pmid = {pmid}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF affected_edges is empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE  // retracted paper wasn't in our graph
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      588[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         log "Retraction detected: PMID {pmid} affects {count} edges"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      589[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      590[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each edge in affected_edges:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      591[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Remove the retracted provenance entry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      592[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             updated_provenance = edge.provenance EXCLUDING entries with pmid = {pmid}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      593[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             new_support_count = edge.support_count - 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      594[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      595[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF new_support_count == 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      596[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // Retracted paper was the only source. Mark edge as retracted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      597[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 update edge in Neptune:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      598[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     status = "RETRACTED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      599[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     retraction_date = current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      600[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     retraction_pmid = pmid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      601[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      602[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // Other papers still support this relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      603[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // Recalculate evidence score without the retracted source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      604[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 new_evidence_score = recalculate_score(updated_provenance)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      605[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 update edge in Neptune:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      606[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     provenance = updated_provenance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      607[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     support_count = new_support_count
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      608[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_score = new_evidence_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      609[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     last_updated = current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      610[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     // Add a flag noting a source was retracted
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      611[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     has_retracted_source = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      612[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      613[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Send notification for high-impact retractions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      614[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF any affected edge has support_count == 0 OR evidence_score was > 0.85:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      615[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             send alert to review queue: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      616[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 retracted_pmid: pmid,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      617[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 affected_edges: count,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      618[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 edges_fully_retracted: count where new support = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      619[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      620[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
